>that turn out to be false. Can you at least tell me whether this 
>statement is true or false so I can figure out the proof or counter-
>example? 
>
>[Thoughts]
>r|s => there exists x such that rx=s.
>If the statement is true then we need s|r, i.e. rx|r, i.e. there 
>exists y such that rxy=r, which means that xy=1. (1 exists since R 
>is an integral domain)So we need x being a unit in R. But I couldn't 
>figure out how to prove that x is a unit. 
